      <h2 id="workflow-automation">Workflow Automation for Common Permit Types</h2>
      
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p>Different permit types require different tracking workflows. Here's how to automate the most common HVAC permits:</p>
        
        <p><strong>Residential HVAC Installation Permits:</strong><br>
        Trigger: Job scheduled with "New Installation" service type<br>
        Workflow: Auto-generate permit application → Submit 7 days before install → Schedule inspection 1 day after completion → Upload certificate to customer file<br>
        Timeline: 10-14 business days total</p>
        
        <p><strong>Commercial Equipment Permits:</strong><br>
        Trigger: Job value exceeds $10,000 threshold<br>
        Workflow: Generate multiple permit applications (mechanical, electrical, fire) → Track each permit separately → Coordinate sequential inspections → Generate compliance report<br>
        Timeline: 21-45 business days depending on complexity</p>
        
        <p><strong>Ductwork Modification Permits:</strong><br>
        Trigger: Service includes "Ductwork" or "Ventilation" categories<br>
        Workflow: Auto-determine permit requirements based on scope → Submit applications → Schedule inspections after rough-in and completion → Archive documentation<br>
        Timeline: 7-10 business days for residential, 14-21 for commercial</p>
        
        <p><strong>Emergency Repair Permits:</strong><br>
        Trigger: Job marked as "Emergency" with permit-required equipment<br>
        Workflow: Generate after-the-fact permit application → Schedule expedited inspection → Pay emergency processing fees → Document compliance<br>
        Timeline: 3-5 business days (varies by municipality)</p>
      </div>

      <div style="background-color: #fff3cd; padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 8px; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #856404;">Pro Tip: Jurisdiction-Specific Workflows</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">Create separate workflows for each municipality you serve. Permit requirements, timelines, and inspection processes vary significantly between jurisdictions. What works in one city may not apply 20 miles away.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Track success rates by jurisdiction and adjust workflows based on actual approval times. Some permit offices consistently take longer than published timelines, especially during busy seasons.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="compliance-reporting">Compliance Reporting and Documentation</h2>
      
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p>Proper permit documentation protects your business from liability and demonstrates compliance during insurance audits or legal proceedings. Your permit tracking system should generate these essential reports:</p>
        
        <p><strong>Active Permits Dashboard:</strong> Real-time view of all pending permits with status, deadlines, and required actions. Update daily to prevent missed deadlines.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Compliance Summary Reports:</strong> Monthly reports showing permit compliance rates, average approval times, and jurisdiction-specific performance. Use for process improvement and insurance documentation.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Audit Trail Documentation:</strong> Complete records of permit applications, approvals, inspections, and certificates organized by project. Essential for warranty claims and liability protection.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Renewal Tracking:</strong> Reports identifying permits approaching expiration dates, especially important for multi-phase commercial projects that span several months.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Cost Analysis Reports:</strong> Track permit fees by jurisdiction, permit type, and time period. Use for accurate job costing and identifying process inefficiencies.</p>
        
        <p>Archive all permit documentation for minimum 7 years (longer for commercial projects). Digital storage through your HVAC software ensures accessibility and prevents document loss due to office disasters or staff turnover.</p>
      </div>

